    Post mortem:

    Should have established the existence of an armed conflict

        specifically, should have declared it was a NIAC

        should have analyzed the weapons systems use by the Russians

        there's a political argument that since the hospital was unmarked, it was not a protected place

    PROTECTED PLACES

        hospitals, undefended places, churches, places of cultural property

        hospitals should be marked, but the mark is not dispositive

        you can attack a hospital when it's been weaponized

            it loses its protected status

            the presence of a belligerent is not a license to kill civilians

            there's always self-defense as a last resort if there are soldiers pinned down

            you can also employ techniques like warning shots to clear the area

    Sub-Assignment:

        monitor the ICC trial against the Timbuktu Library destruction suspect

    Hague Rules on Targeting:

        distinguish
            lawful combatants
            unlawful combatants
            civilians

        when a lawful combatant is captured, he is a POW

        when an unlawful combatant is captured, he is a detainee
            to be prosecuted under the laws of the locality

        Hamdan v Rumsfeld

            first time SCOTUS used an international law as precedent

        civilians are protected

            civilians accompanying the force are treated as non-civilians
            theyre treated like lawful combatants

        noncombatants

            doctors, chaplins, and anyone assigned to a medical unit
            and
            those out of combat
                POWs
                wounded, sick, and shipwrecked
                parachutists

            medical personnel have a right to protect themselves and their patience

        PLACES

            you can attack a place of cultural value or a hospital if it has lost its protected status

            protected status is lost when a place is weaponized

        PROPERTY AND PROTECTED PLACES

            false use of protective emblems is a reason to ignore the protective emblem

            military objectives:

                military equpiment
                buildings
                factories
                transportation
                communications

            take care to analyze the collateral results of a given action

            PROTECTED PROPERTY:

                civilian property
                fixed and mobile hospitals
                medical transport
                cultural property
                    dedicated to the arts, sciences, religion, education, history, and charity
                objects indispensable to the survival of civilians
                works and installations containing dangerous forces
                    a chemical factory bomb aftermath could become a chlorine attack
                    a nuclear plant might create a meltdown

                usually protected, but can become targets if they're weaponized

            PROTECTIVE EMBLEMS

                MEDICAL EMBLEMS

                    now, it's only the red cross, the red diamond, and the red crescent

                    if it's not marked with one of the three emblems, it's not protected

                CULTURAL EMBLEM

                    blue and white down-pointing pentagon

                    it protects a cultural place

                        no attacking unless it becomes a weapon


    WEAPONS

        All weapons must be reviewed by the TJAG for legal suffiency

        THE TEST:

            Is a weapon or munitions' acquisition or use consistent witht he law of war and arms control treaties to which the US is a state party, or customary international law?

                [whether the employment of a weapon for its normal or expected use inevitably would cause injury or suffering manifestly disproportionate to its military effectiveness]

        ILLEGAL PER SE:

            barbed lances

            projectiles filled with glass

            improperly used weapons (notched FMJ rounds, eg)

            prohibited by treaty

            expanding bullets (dum dum bullets)

            hollow point bullets

            land mines (except in Korea, and except for self-neutralizing)

            booby traps

            poison and poisoned rounds

            chemical weapons

                riot control agents get special treatment

            biological weapons

        PRESUMPTIVELY LEGAL

            incendiaries

                napalm, flamethrowers, thermite, tracer, white phosphorous

                all lawful if used properly

            lasers

                lawful if not blinding

            nuclear weapons

                no customary or IL prohibition
                some treaties limit the use

        FIRST USE RENOUNCED

            herbicides

                no first use, except domestically and to control veg in defensive areas
                the medical fallout of agent orange made this a political problem

            chemical weapons used for riot control

    A lawful combatant

        wear insignia
        wear a uniform
            (these first two are no longer strict requirements)
        chain of command
        carry arms openly

    there's no conspiracy at the international level

        but aiding and abetting theory is available

        but right now we can't really directly hold accountable the corporations and nations

        command involvement theory might be available someday

    TACTICS

        Psychological Operations

            lawful
            used extensively in the cold war

            operation desert storm "the saddam leaflet"

                we promised to destroy a particular division
                then we did destroy them
                dropped leaflet promises
                lived up to them
                then they started surrendering

        Ruses and Deception

            injuring the enemy by legitimate deception
            deception lawful

                we faked a marine invasion off the kuwaiti coast

            fighting in enemy uniforms and flags is inadvisable [and perhaps illegal?]

                if they're caught by the enemy in an enemy uniform, no LOAC protections

                BUT:

                Article 39. â€“ Emblems of nationality

                    2. It is prohibited to make use of the flags or military emblems, insignia or uniforms of adverse Parties while engaging in attacks or to shield, favour, protect or impede military operations.

        Treachery and Perfidy (feigning and misuse)

            perfidy involves injuring the enemy by his adherence of the law of war

                hiding behind a white flag
                using women and children as a shield
                feigning surrender or incapacitation
                misuse of the red cross
                feigning civilian status

        Assassination

            it's the politically motivated targeted killing of a person

            national policy prohibits assassination

            all prohibited:

                hiring assassins
                putting a price on a head
                offering rewards for dead or alive

            it's bad policy because it opens Pandora's box

        Espionage

            acting clandestinely to obtain info for transmission back to their side

            gathering intel in uniform is not espionage

            espionage is not a violation of LOAC

            no protection for spies under the GC's

            spies are tried under the laws of the capturing nation

        Reprisals

            conduct which would otherwise be unlawful
            resorted to by one belligerent
            against enemy personnel or property
            in response to a violation of LOAC
            for the purpose of enforcing future compliance

        RULES OF ENGAGEMENT

            commander's tool
            applying the LOAC to the mission

            directives issued by the officer that delineate the limitations
                for initiation and engagement with other forces

            ROE are drafted in consideration of
                LOAC
                national policy
                public opinion
                military operational constraints

            sometimes more restrictive than what's required by the LAOC

    WAR CRIMES

        war crimes act of 1996 (97?)
            grave breaches as defined in GC 1949
            violations of hague convention IV
            violations of common article 3

        a military commander has authority to prosecute civilians in a theater of operations
            under the uniform code of military justice
            where no locl authority is present to do the job
            though we have not done it yet

            we prosecuted blackwater for recon by fire

        everyone in the force, with the force, or contracting to serve the force is bound

        command responsibility

            the private is liable
            the top comman all the way up to CinC is liable

            General Yamashita was the first to be prosecuted under this theory

            the commander is personally directly liable for acts he knew of or shoulda

        investigative assests and reporting

            we have an obligation to report investigate and prosecute or else hand it over

            we have the criminal investigation divisions to do the investigation

                also JAGS, IGs, US Attorney

    TERRORISM, DIRTY LITTLE WARS, and KALEIDOSCOPIC CONFLICT

